<div id="review_890120395" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/890120395" />
    <a title="Bonnie Brody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7630898-bonnie-brody"><img alt="Bonnie Brody" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571268702p2/7630898.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/890120395?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bonnie Brody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bonnie Brody" href="/user/show/7630898-bonnie-brody">Bonnie Brody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer890120395" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11478382895323580185">Clement has a natural way with words. Her narrative is somewhat minimalist in style yet incorporates a lot of magical realism. <br/><br/>The chapters follow the life of Ladydi who lives with her mother in a mountain village about an hour away from Acapulco. Rita, Ladydi&apos;s mother, is an alcoholic. There are no men in the village. After they&apos;ve fathered children, they leave for the big city or the United States. The novel follows Ladydi from her village to Acapulco and further.<br/><br/>Ladydi and the other girls are</span>
  <span id="freeText11478382895323580185" style="display:none">Clement has a natural way with words. Her narrative is somewhat minimalist in style yet incorporates a lot of magical realism. <br /><br />The chapters follow the life of Ladydi who lives with her mother in a mountain village about an hour away from Acapulco. Rita, Ladydi's mother, is an alcoholic. There are no men in the village. After they've fathered children, they leave for the big city or the United States. The novel follows Ladydi from her village to Acapulco and further.<br /><br />Ladydi and the other girls are made to look ugly. Their teeth are painted black with magic marker, charcoal is spread on their faces, and they are dressed in boy's clothing. In fact, Ladydi is called 'Boy'. This is to prevent the girls from being kidnapped by the drug traffickers who regularly come into the village to steal girls. Paula, the most beautiful girl in the village, is kidnapped and later returns a changed person. Paula "should have been a legend. Her face should have covered magazines. Love songs should have been written to her." Instead, purchased for $500, she becomes a mistress to a man named McClane, named after a character in a Bruce Willis movie. <br /><br />The novel is intriguing but I found the narrative choppy and somewhat repetitive. Though the writing is good, things don't fit together well and the chapters don't blend one into the other with ease. The book is more like a series of vignettes about Ladydi's life. I found the characterizations lacking in depth and wished for more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11478382895323580185" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


