    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1226489453" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1226489453" />
    <a title="Jill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2228181-jill"><img alt="Jill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507660688p2/2228181.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1226489453?book_show_action=true">Mar 13, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jill" href="/user/show/2228181-jill">Jill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1226489453" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3586088888616264702">Being born beautiful – looking, say, like Jennifer Lopez – is, for most women, akin to winning the lottery.<br/><br/>Except, that is, if you are born in the remote mountains of Guerrero, Mexico.<br/><br/>Ladydi Garcia Martinez, a young girl trying to reach adulthood in a land where drug traffickers routinely steal the most beautiful adolescents and force them into prostitution, and her close-knit group of girlfriends are just trying to survive. One of her friends, is stunningly beautiful – a Jennifer Lopez clone. A</span>
  <span id="freeText3586088888616264702" style="display:none">Being born beautiful – looking, say, like Jennifer Lopez – is, for most women, akin to winning the lottery.<br /><br />Except, that is, if you are born in the remote mountains of Guerrero, Mexico.<br /><br />Ladydi Garcia Martinez, a young girl trying to reach adulthood in a land where drug traffickers routinely steal the most beautiful adolescents and force them into prostitution, and her close-knit group of girlfriends are just trying to survive. One of her friends, is stunningly beautiful – a Jennifer Lopez clone. Another, the more fortunate Maria, is born with a harelip and as a result, is able to walk around in relative safety.<br /><br />Ladydi – named for Princess Diana, because her mother loved any woman to whom a man had been unfaithful, recalls THIS as her first memory: “Now we make you ugly, my mother said. She whistled. Her mouth was so close she sprayed my neck with her white-spit. I could smell beer. In the mirror I watched her move the piece of charcoal across my face. It’s a nasty life, she whispered.”<br /><br />In deceptively childlike, yet often lyrical, prose, Ms. Clement narrates Ladydi’s harrowing young life: blackening her face and cutting her hair so she would not look attractive, hiding in holes if she hears drug traffickers approaching, diving for safety when army helicopters arrive, spraying the poisonous Paraquat everywhere except for the poppy fields that are the key to millions of dollars in drugs. Girls are worth so very little in Guerrero: “A missing woman is just another leaf that goes down the gutter in a rainstorm,” Ladydi’s mother says.<br /><br />The trajectory of Ladydi’s life could easily be overly dramatized. But Jennifer Clement does not get overly manipulative or indulgent. The result is a book that sings with the ring of truth and shines a spotlight on the mistreatment of girls and women without the spotlight ever becoming too glaring. I felt that the first half of the book, in particular, was breathtaking in its descriptions. And it affirmed my belief that the invisible and damaged people who live in our midst often deserve our compassion. This is a high 4-star book.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3586088888616264702" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


