        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer760146578" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3654906906437556740">WOW! Very rarely do I find a book that leaves me in my mind wondering... In the beginning I was a little confused at the present and past tense status&apos; running simultaneously.. Jennifer Clement did a wonderful job bringing the two into an artfully written novel of tragedy and love interwoven with a social dynamic that most American women have no Idea would even exist! Ladydi the main character tells of her life and the tragedy of being born a girl. Even worse a beautiful girl. The minimized horr</span>
  <span id="freeText3654906906437556740" style="display:none">WOW! Very rarely do I find a book that leaves me in my mind wondering... In the beginning I was a little confused at the present and past tense status' running simultaneously.. Jennifer Clement did a wonderful job bringing the two into an artfully written novel of tragedy and love interwoven with a social dynamic that most American women have no Idea would even exist! Ladydi the main character tells of her life and the tragedy of being born a girl. Even worse a beautiful girl. The minimized horrors of growing up near drug "farms" poisons, brutal natural elements and drug lords. I feel like this would be an excellent book for someone interested in social work and anyone who despises immigration. Ladydi suffered the loss of family and community and still comes out in the end with apparent hope and optimism despite what life has shown her. </span>
