<div id="review_3668654562" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3668654562" />
    <a title="Berit Lundqvist" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63886959-berit-lundqvist"><img alt="Berit Lundqvist" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1487288361p2/63886959.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3668654562?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Berit Lundqvist" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Berit Lundqvist" href="/user/show/63886959-berit-lundqvist">Berit Lundqvist</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/63886959-berit-lundqvist?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3668654562" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17913483491340973674">An absolutely horrifying book about corruption, drugs, and human trafficing in the Mexican countryside. The book is based on a number of interviews with women who actually have been victims of human trafficing, but is boiled down to a story seen through the eyes of Ladydi, a teenage girl living outside Acapulco.<br/><br/>And it sure contains all the classic elements of misery:<br/>Estranged fathers. Check.<br/>Endless poverty. Check.<br/>Drug dealers and drug cartels. Check.<br/>Guns in abundance. Check.<br/>Kidnappings. Check.<br/>Se</span>
  <span id="freeText17913483491340973674" style="display:none">An absolutely horrifying book about corruption, drugs, and human trafficing in the Mexican countryside. The book is based on a number of interviews with women who actually have been victims of human trafficing, but is boiled down to a story seen through the eyes of Ladydi, a teenage girl living outside Acapulco.<br /><br />And it sure contains all the classic elements of misery:<br />Estranged fathers. Check.<br />Endless poverty. Check.<br />Drug dealers and drug cartels. Check.<br />Guns in abundance. Check.<br />Kidnappings. Check.<br />Sexual abuse. Check.<br />Corrupt cops. Check.<br /><br />And no light at the end of the tunnel. No hope whatsoever. This is the kind of book that makes you lose the last of your hope for humanity. And for men in particular. A brilliant and important book, though.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17913483491340973674" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


