<div id="review_868761604" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/868761604" />
    <a title="Thomas Williams" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3586502-thomas-williams"><img alt="Thomas Williams" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610024059p2/3586502.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/868761604?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas Williams" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas Williams" href="/user/show/3586502-thomas-williams">Thomas Williams</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer868761604" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7455701570972750940">(from my review in the WSJ)<br/><br/>By THOMAS CHATTERTON WILLIAMS<br/>Feb. 28, 2014 2:08 p.m. ET<br/>&apos;The best thing you can be in Mexico is an ugly girl,&quot; Ladydi says. She is the 13-year-old narrator of Jennifer Clement&apos;s beautiful, heart-rending novel, &quot;Prayers for the Stolen.&quot; Her first name pays tribute to the late Princess Diana, yet Ladydi&apos;s circumstances in a nameless mountain village in the state of Guerrero, an hour&apos;s drive from the glitzy beaches of Acapulco, could hardly be farther from royalty. Situate</span>
  <span id="freeText7455701570972750940" style="display:none">(from my review in the WSJ)<br /><br />By THOMAS CHATTERTON WILLIAMS<br />Feb. 28, 2014 2:08 p.m. ET<br />'The best thing you can be in Mexico is an ugly girl," Ladydi says. She is the 13-year-old narrator of Jennifer Clement's beautiful, heart-rending novel, "Prayers for the Stolen." Her first name pays tribute to the late Princess Diana, yet Ladydi's circumstances in a nameless mountain village in the state of Guerrero, an hour's drive from the glitzy beaches of Acapulco, could hardly be farther from royalty. Situated amid poppy fields and heroin labs, her village is populated by single mothers and daughters. It is "a hot land of rubber plants, snakes, iguanas and scorpions, the blond, transparent scorpions, which were hard to see and that kill." Danger also comes from the air in the form of payloads of toxic herbicide that the government's pilots, too scared to deliver to the cartel poppy fields that are their intended targets, let fall over the community instead. It is a perilous terrain that the women must navigate alone, as all their men have long since abandoned them for the north in search of better fortunes.<br /><br />Without any men around, the girls and even some of the women are fruit on a low-hanging tree, waiting to be plucked by the teams of cartel henchmen that periodically descend on their homes in cavalcades, on the lookout for new bodies to sell into slavery. And so Ladydi's mother, like all the other mothers, rubs charcoal on her face and marker on her teeth to make them look rotten. The town's sole beautician laments that "I have to make little girls look like boys, I have to make the older girls look plain, and I have to make pretty girls look ugly." In that way, it is Ladydi's best friend and half-sister, Maria, born with a disfiguring harelip, and not her breathtaking neighbor Paula, whom luck has chosen.<br /><br />We follow Ladydi, Maria and Paula, and another friend, Estefani, as they flower into adolescence, complete the atrociously inadequate schooling available on their mountain and go their separate directions. The story of their young lives is set in stark relief against the withering sadness of their mothers' petty fates. Estefani's father, who diligently sends money and gifts from the U.S., also brings her mother HIV on one of his annual visits. Maria's and Ladydi's mothers shared the same philandering man; his absence haunts the book as Ladydi comes to realize why Maria looks the way she does and why her mother has sunk into a deep and bitter alcoholism. It's worse for Paula's mother, the erstwhile mistress of a rich man from Acapulco, who must go into hiding with her dangerously pretty daughter after she escapes from a stint of concubinage that has reduced her to a dazed, childlike state of confusion. "I was a plastic water bottle," Paula tells Ladydi in a moment of lucidity. "Something you pick up and take a swig of."<br /><br />Such fiercely observed comparisons of human and inanimate life form a continuing motif throughout the story. "I felt like counterfeit money, fake designer clothing at the Acapulco market," Ladydi observes later, after her own run-in with tragedy, "like a Virgin of Guadalupe made in China." Ms. Clement, who is American but has spent decades living in Mexico, achieves the formidable feat of smooth, clear English that pulses with an energy and sensibility that is convincingly Latin American. Her authority is such that one quickly forgets that she is describing a country and plight not her own.<br /><br />Beyond the lapidary prose and indefatigable humor that suffuses even the book's darkest passages, it is the novel's focus on depicting the sordid reality below the border—the full-blown humanitarian crisis there—that makes the narrative so compelling. And yet the book doesn't function as a tract or polemic. This isn't a protest novel dressing up sociology as art. Nor do we encounter a cast of angelic victims. Life's injustice alone can't explain Ladydi's father's disgraceful behavior.<br /><br />"Prayers for the Stolen" is a powerful read, similar—if on a much smaller scale—to what the late Chilean writer Roberto Bolaño accomplished in "2666," with his depiction of the mass murders taking place in Ciudad Juárez. Like Bolaño, Ms. Clement both spins a captivating yarn and paints a terrifying picture of the price paid by people whose lives are upended by globalization and a nightmarish drug economy. The only thing magical about this realism is the marvel of human resilience in the face of tragedy.<br /><br />—Mr. Williams is the author of the memoir "Losing My Cool."</span>
  <a data-text-id="7455701570972750940" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


