<div id="review_1182315203" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1182315203" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3680008-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641853236p2/3680008.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1182315203?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/3680008-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1182315203" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4543443119175229413">Ladydi Garcia Martinez is a fierce young girl but only acknowledged as a boy. According to her mother, living as a girl is not a blessing but a curse. Perceived to be a boy, she operates in the realm of one. Tough and adamant, her mother word is the only thing that matters. Even if her mother sounds unreasonable at times, she knows that she cannot question her, knowing that she will have severe consequences. As far as the relationship that she share with her father, is nonexistent in her opinion</span>
  <span id="freeText4543443119175229413" style="display:none">Ladydi Garcia Martinez is a fierce young girl but only acknowledged as a boy. According to her mother, living as a girl is not a blessing but a curse. Perceived to be a boy, she operates in the realm of one. Tough and adamant, her mother word is the only thing that matters. Even if her mother sounds unreasonable at times, she knows that she cannot question her, knowing that she will have severe consequences. As far as the relationship that she share with her father, is nonexistent in her opinion. Caught between believing the beliefs of her mother, Laydia must find a way for her voice to shine. Narrated by a strong female character, this was a memorable book about redemption, hope and survival.<br /><br />I am not going to lie, I was partially confused with the content of the book. Hence I skipped some pages, cause it just was not really as consistent as I would like. However the one thing that made this book amazing was the characterization, that saved the mediocre rating. Sometimes there are books that are amazing because of the development of characters, not so much the subject matter of the book. I can't put my finger on what made this book so special, but I was very impressed after finishing it.<br /><br />Looking forward o reading more books by Clement!</span>
  <a data-text-id="4543443119175229413" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


